# App Directory & Routing

The [src/app](mdc:web/src/app) directory implements the Next.js App Router structure.

- **[layout.tsx](mdc:web/src/app/layout.tsx)**: Root layout for all pages.
- **[page.tsx](mdc:web/src/app/page.tsx)**: Main entry point for the homepage (if present).
- **Subfolders**: Organize routes and features (e.g., [admin](mdc:web/src/app/sysAdmin), [api](mdc:web/src/app/api), [(auth)](mdc:web/src/app/(auth))
- **Nested Routing**: Each folder can have its own `page.tsx` and `layout.tsx` for nested routes and layouts.

### Store admin (`storeAdmin/(dashboard)/[storeId]`)

- **One layout for the store segment:** `StoreAdminLayout`, `checkStoreStaffAccess`, and `getStoreWithRelations` live in [`[storeId]/layout.tsx`](mdc:web/src/app/storeAdmin/(dashboard)/[storeId]/layout.tsx) only.
- The [`(routes)`](mdc:web/src/app/storeAdmin/(dashboard)/[storeId]/(routes)) folder is for **colocating pages** (dashboard, orders, `notifications/…`, etc.). It must **not** contain a `layout.tsx`. A nested `(...)/[storeId]/(routes)/layout.tsx` previously led to **spurious 404s** on deep paths (e.g. `notifications/history`) in dev with Turbopack, even though `next build` listed the route.
- New store-admin pages: add `.../(routes)/<feature>/page.tsx` (or another segment under `[storeId]`) without introducing a second layout under `(routes)`.

See [Next.js App Router documentation](mdc:https:/nextjs.org/docs/app/building-your-application/routing) for more details.
